11 Apr 2014
CHP notified of 3 additional human cases of avian influenza A(H7N9) in Mainland
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Centre for Health Protection (CHP) of the Department of Health (DH) yesterday ([10 Apr 2014]) received notification of 3 additional human cases of avian influenza A(H7N9) from the Health and Family Planning Commission of Guangdong Province.

The patients include a woman aged 81 in Guangzhou, a man aged 37 in Shantou and a woman aged 71 in Heyuan. All of them are now hospitalised for treatment.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of cases of laboratory confirmed human infection with avian influenza A(H7N9) virus in China continues to increase. As of yesterday, 14 Apr 2014, there were 407 cases reported. Zhejiang continues as the province reporting the most number of cases (138), with Guangdong now increasing in reported cases (102). As can be seen in the WHO update above, the majority of cases continue to have defined histories of exposure to poultry prior to onset of illness. Given the insidious nature of low pathogenic avian influenza viruses (LPAI), where infected avians are primarily asymptomatic, the presence of the LPAI A(H7N9) in domestic poultry stock in Mainland China, and the cultural practice of preferring to slaughter poultry immediately prior to preparing for consumption either through maintenance of backyard flocks or through "wet markets" (markets selling live poultry) in this situation is a continued recipe for transmission of the avian influenza A(H7N9) to humans in China - a significant challenge for the public health sector.

For a map of China showing provinces, see http://www.sacu.org/maps/provmap.png. The HealthMap/ProMED map of China can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2405179,155. - Mod.MPP]
